Role of Methylation Quantitative Trait Loci in Shear Stress Susceptibility for Atherosclerosis

Ruben Methorst, Bsc, Dr. Sander W. Van der Laan, Dr. Michal Mokry, Prof. dr. Gerard Pasterkamp

22-10-2019

Introduction

Here we present the scripts and data corresponding with above stated publication. We performed several in silico analysis, including methylation quantitative trait loci (cis-mQTL) analysis using QTLtool v1.1 and Two Sample Mendelian Randomisation (2SMR) using TwoSampleMR v0.4.22.

Data was obtained from several sources. mQTL analysis was performed in genotyping and methylation data from the AtheroExpress Biobank1. 2SMR was performed using CARDIoGRAM+C4D2 and METASTROKE3 GWAS summary statistics.

cis-mQTL analysis

cis-mQTL was perfomed using readily built scripts by S.W. Van der Laan, Associate Professor UMC Utrecht.

Data preparation

We extracted our regions of interest from the Illumina 450k manifest file. Only looked at our 11 genes of interest and only at CpGs within -2000 TSS and 1st exon. A range of +/- 250kb was used on this region of interest to analyse for mQTLs using QTLtools4.

library(readr)
library(data.table)

#read data

CPG <- read.delim("CPG.txt", header = FALSE)

Illumina450K <- read_csv("HumanMethylation450_15017482_v1-2.csv")

#extract genes of interest

IlluminaREGIONS <- Illumina450K[grep("KLF4|HOXA5|TMEM184B|ADAMTSL5|KLF3|CMKLR1|PKP4|ACVRL1|DOK4|SPRY2|ENOSF1",
                                  Illumina450K$UCSC_RefGene_Name), ]

Illumina_data <- IlluminaREGIONS[-grep("Body|3'UTR", IlluminaREGIONS$UCSC_RefGene_Group), ]

ROI <- data.frame(Illumina_data$IlmnID, Illumina_data$UCSC_RefGene_Name, Illumina_data$Chromosome_36, Illumina_data$Coordinate_36, Illumina_data$Coordinate_36, Illumina_data$Strand)

#Range, lead, trait column added

range <- numeric(157)

ROI["range"] <- range

ROI$range <- 250000


lead <- numeric(157)
ROI["lead"] <- lead

ROI$lead <- "new_lead"

trait <- numeric(157)
ROI["trait"] <- trait

ROI$trait <- "SS"

#prepare first row

ROI[1, 8] <- "previous_&_new_lead"

#to and from column added

ROI$from <- ROI$Illumina_data.Coordinate_36

ROI$to <- ROI$Illumina_data.Coordinate_36

#change names

colnames(ROI)[1:4] <- c("CpG", "Gene", "Chr", "Location")

#re-order

ROI2 <- ROI[c(1, 2, 3, 4, 10, 11, 7, 8, 9)]

#from to change values to TSS and -/+ 250kb

REGIONS <- ROI2

REGIONS$from[REGIONS$from %like% "^1590"] <- "158771722"
REGIONS$from[REGIONS$from %like% "^383"] <- "38092185"

Regional Association Plot KLF3

We made the regional association plot of the KLF3 region using Regional Association ComparER (RACER) v0.1 of oliviasabik.

#Download & Install RACER tool
# install.packages("devtools")
# library(devtools)
# install_github("oliviasabik/RACER")
  library(RACER)


library(readr)
library(dplyr)

#read data

RAP_data_1 <- read_delim("LocusZoom data 1.csv",
                               ";", escape_double = FALSE, trim_ws = TRUE)


RAP_data_1[,-1] <- gsub("\\:.*", "", as.matrix(RAP_data_1[,-1]))

RAP_data_1 <- RAP_data_1[grepl("cg18361445", RAP_data_1$ProbeID), ]


RAP_data_1$Nominal_P <- as.numeric(gsub(",", ".", RAP_data_1$Nominal_P))

#Regional association plot

mQTLs_plot <- RACER::formatRACER(assoc_data = RAP_data_1,
                                 chr_col = 3,
                                 pos_col = 4,
                                 p_col = 32)

#Add LD data

mQTLs_plot_2 <- RACER::ldRACER(assoc_data = mQTLs_plot,
                               rs_col = 2, pops = "EUR",
                               lead_snp = "rs7660114")

#plotting data

mQTLs_plot_3 <- mQTLs_plot_2[mQTLs_plot_2$LOG10P > 0, ]

RACER::singlePlotRACER(assoc_data = mQTLs_plot_3,
                       chr = 4,
                       build = "hg19",
                       plotby = "coord",
                       start_plot = 38416416,
                       end_plot = 38926476)
